solve(BendersOptimizationData) - Method in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersAlgorithm
 
solveProblem(Double[][], boolean, boolean) - Method in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersAlgorithm
Solves a SimplexTableau with Simplex or BranchAndBound.

Solution format:
{10d, 0d, 130d, 2d}
Last value represents the solution type.
Second to last represents optimal function value.
The rest represent variable values.
For more information see return of Simplex.loese().
steps - Variable in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersSolutionData
 
stepZeroCut(MasterProblem, SubProblem, Problem, Double[]) - Method in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersAlgorithm
This method calculates the first cut in step 0, with all u-values set to 0 and adds the cut to the MasterProblem.

To set all u-values to 0 all function values are set to 0.
The SimplexTableau is then solved as usual.
subProblem - Variable in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersStepData
Tableau needs to be given in this way:
{{1d, 2d, 0d, 0d, 200d}, restriction 1
{1d, 0d, 0d, 0d, 50d}, restriction 2
{0d, 0d, 1d, 0d, 80d}, restriction 3
{0d, 0d, 3d, 10d, 500d}} function
SubProblem - Class in FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders
 
SubProblem(Double[][], List<Double[]>) - Constructor for class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.SubProblem
Initializes a sub problem by a given simplex tableau.

Tableau needs to be given in this way:
{{1d, 2d, 0d, 0d, 200d}, restriction 1
{1d, 0d, 0d, 0d, 50d}, restriction 2
{0d, 0d, 1d, 0d, 80d}, restriction 3
{0d, 0d, 3d, 10d, 500d}} function
subSolution - Variable in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersStepData
Example for solution object:
{0d, 0d, 3d, 10d, 500d, 3.0}

500d is the objective function value
last value (here 3.0) is an additional info about the solution.
substituteConstant(BendersOptimizationData) - Method in class FPP.LinearOptimization.Model.benders.BendersAlgorithm
This method substitutes the constant of the simplex tableau function with 0 and returns that constant.
This is done because Simplex & BAndB can not handle that in the right way.

If there is no constant in the function, Double.NaN is returned.
ATTENTION: constant value has to be added to the optimal solution to get the right result!
